-- ==============================================
-- FILE: page_text_new.sql
-- GENERATED: 20260517062330
-- ==============================================
REPLACE INTO `page_text`
(
    `entry`,
    `text`,
    `next_page`
)
VALUES
(4000, 'How to Use Your Airtime Voucher


Find a mailbox—any mailbox’ll do.

Address your mail to Everlook.

Write your pitch in the message. Keep it snappy, yeah? Time is gold!

Attach your Airtime Voucher and hit send.


Your ad’ll hit the airwaves next week. Keep it lawful and civil—goblins run a business, not a circus!

Get ready to be famous, kid!', 0),
(50734, 'The pirates of Plunder Island were eager to ravage the wealthy Balor. Now knowing how to navigate the seas around the island, they had the element of surprise on their side. And thus the first Siege of Balor began, with an armada of vessels creeping in from the horizon. Day after day the pirates drew in closer to the island, showing their nautical prowess by evading the rocky reefs using their newly acquired knowledge.', 0),
(50735, 'The citizens were distraught, begging for Duke Balor to save them from their doom. Stormwrought Castle may have been well fortified, but the rest of the isle was defenseless before the rampaging swashbucklers and the few ships they possessed were not enough to halt their advances. Corralling the populace into the castle was the only thing he could do for now.', 0),
(50736, 'The siege was relentless. With only a few men and women able to defend the keep, the morale was low. It was not to stay that way, as Duke Balor''s daughter Daria once more rallied the people to defend their home and their future. Commanding others to mount the few siege weapons they had, she herself took the charge in direct combat, leading those able to fight. Fierce battles were fought and with many Arathi veterans on their side, the people of Balor were able to push the pirates back.', 0),
(50737, 'Their celebration was cut short, however, as the Lord of Plunder Isle himself entered the battlefield and the fighting began anew. Swords clashed and bodies fell to the ground. Daria herself was up against the pirate lord.', 0),
(50738, 'They engaged in a violent duel, with one strike of their weapons more vicious than the last. The Duke''s daughter was able to outrange her opponent with her halberd, but struggled with keeping up against the incredible speed of his saber. Pushing her further and further into a corner, the pirate lord knew how to counter her range advantage.', 0),
(50739, 'Daria herself was a competent fighter, but this man she was up against was clearly a battle hardened warrior. But her resolve to save her home was not to falter. She continued parrying his strikes, one by one, completely focusing on the metal of his sword. In her determination, however, she did not notice the dagger he pulled from beneath his coat.', 0),
(50740, 'Even before she could see it, she felt its cold iron in her side. Shocked and caught offguard by his feint, she lost sight of his saber, before quickly getting disarmed. With a grin of malice, the pirate lord thrust the blade into her, ending her life. Those able to witness it were horrified. Her father,  who watched all of it from atop the castle walls could not believe his eyes. Terror, grief and despair all culminated within him at the sight of his daughter''s lifeless body being thrown in front of the castle for all to see.', 0),
(50741, 'Duke Balor was completely mortified and if it had not been for Lord Eugent Grahan, then the castle would''ve been stormed that day. Reminding him of what Daria fought for, he managed to release the Duke from his stupor, causing him to have the remaining forces retreat into Stormwrought Castle.', 0),
(50742, 'Now besieged in his own home. Duke Balor was caught deep in despair, his pride shattered by the pirate assault. Lord Grahan stepped in front of his ruler, and as a beacon of hope, offered a proposition. Telling the duke of his good connections to Stormwind, he promised him a regiment of King Barathen''s men to aid him in his most desperate hour. In turn, Stormwind would have direct authority over Balor.', 0),
(50743, 'Left with little to no choices, he agreed to the terms, under the condition to remain a figurehead for his people. With Lord Grahan assuring him of that, they sent a messenger bird to Stormwind, hoping for a quick and positive answer.', 0),
(50744, 'Days went by, and morale on both ends fluctuated. The pirates'' inability to seize the castle and the rations getting depleted more and more with each passing day factored heavily into each party''s fighting spirit. A few more days; the rations wouldn''t suffice any longer. Laying eyes upon the broken courage of his people, Duke Balor mustered up his strength to address them in their most dire hour.', 0),
(50745, 'With a booming voice he reminded them of their mettle, splitting themselves from Stormwind without certainty; he reminded them of their ingenuity, turning the raw gold they found into a blooming trade port, he reminded them of the pride they have in Balor and all the grandiose feats they accomplished together as one. Before he could continue, a powerful and awe inducing horn could be heard in the distance.', 0),
(50746, 'Taking Lord Grahan with him, the invigorated Duke rushed on top of the castle walls, only to see blue sails adorned with a bright gold at the horizon. King Wrynn kept his promise and with almost double as many ships, he and his men easily overwhelmed the brigands, driving them off the island for good. While the siege was broken, the island had been sacked. Still, Duke Balor was thankful for his and his people''s rescue at the hands of Stormwind''s king; the king he now swore his loyalty to.', 0),
(50747, 'With the help of their new patrons, Balor recovered and soon could begin trade anew. Now protected by the Knights of Stormwind, the small island autonomy could prosper and grow even more. In front of Stormwrought Castle, to commemorate her heroic stand against the assailants, a statue of Daria Balor was erected. For her people, she remained a symbol of hope and resilience ever since.', 0),
(50748, 'After migrating south following the fall of the Empire of Arathor, a large congregation of Arathi settled in the fertile valley of Elwynn, founding the Kingdom of Stormwind. While under the leadership of House Wrynn, the populace enjoyed prosperity and peace, having survived the countless perils and enemies that threw themselves at the young nation.', 0),
(50749, 'Solidifying themselves as the prominent force of the southern parts of the Eastern Kingdoms, the people of Stormwind prided themselves on their newfound independence. With such feelings in heart, it is only natural for some to wish for even greater fortune.', 0),
(50750, 'One such individual was the charismatic Duke Balor, a fairly influential nobleman and merchant, who knew his way around the people. Having discovered an isolated group of islands full of natural resources in the Great Sea west of Stormwind, he gathered a large group of like-minded followers in pursuit of even more wealth.', 0),
(50751, 'It didn''t take long for the settlers to establish a small settlement called Breezehaven, named after the fresh and salty winds circulating their new home. Surely, there were a few settlers doubtful about the Duke''s promises. However, not long after the first mining work started, it was clear that his words could be trusted. The island was filled to the brim with plentiful gold veins, showering the settlers with unprecedented wealth. Using their immense fortune, Balor quickly became its own self-sufficient town, and soon after a valuable merchant port.', 0),
(50752, 'Of course, this did not go unnoticed by King Barathen Wrynn, Monarch of Stormwind. While not fearing that Balor''s current autonomy could pose a threat to Stormwind, he could not deny the potential uses a maritime port could open up for Stormwind. Thus, he ordered the prestigious Grahan family, arguably Stormwind’s most renown merchants, to join Duke Balor on his island, acting as a double agent for the king.', 0),
(50753, 'Becoming a bustling tradepoint for all sorts of goods from far and wide naturally drew the attention of more unsavory folk. Following the years of Balor''s rise, its reputation had found its way into the dens of powerful pirate captains and lords seeking fame and booty. They hailed from Plunder Isle, a lawless off-shoot of another nation founded by Arathi settlers, Kul Tiras. While only facing skirmishes at first, their assaults slowly became more and more daring and vicious.', 0),
(50754, 'Fearing for his and his people''s future, Duke Balor saw desperation draw in closer. Luckily for him, his eldest daughter, Daria Balor, a skilled and thoughtful tactician reminiscent of those in the Empire of Arathor, had a solution to their dilemma. Utilizing the islands'' unique terrain and deadly cliffs to her advantage, she lured the bashful brigands and their ships into seemingly safe waters.', 0),
(50755, 'However, without the knowledge that the people of Balor possess, there would be no way these pirates could navitage the perilous reefs. The scoundrel vessels crashed against the steep rocks, sinking below the surface to their watery tombs.', 0),
(50756, 'Daria''s strategy proved successful: the pirates were driven off, and she was heralded as Balor''s heroine. A grand feast was held for five days straight, filled with laughter and joy, celebrating the island''s prosperity and rescued existence. Unbeknownst to the cheerful crowd, however, was trouble brewing across the sea.', 0),
(50757, 'Furious about his severe loss at the hands of Duke Balor''s daughter, the Lord of Plunder Isle was not about to let that impertinent woman trample on his honor as the famed regent over Azeroth''s seas. As if fate had dictated it - he had a trump card at his disposal: one of his surviving crews was able to capture a terrified citizen, that oozed cowardice out of every pore. Greedy and unloyal, he accepted the offer he had been given without second thought. With his knowledge, the pirate ships would finally be able to navigate the ruthless sea of Balor.', 0),
(50758, 'The lands of Northwind are governed by three great houses of Stormwind nobility. While the King still reigns supreme over the vale, the three houses keep order and maintain the functionalities of its regional facilities.', 0),
(50759, 'Lord Percival Amberwood, fourth descendant of the Amberwood lineage, oversees the region as a whole. All citizens of Northwind answer to him and his wise decisions. Beloved by many, his way of ruling follows a more calculated way compared to that of his father.', 0),
(50760, 'Sir Nathaniel Amberwood, brother to Lord Amberwood, did not inherit his rule, even though he is the older brother. Many presume this fact to be the reason behind Sir Amberwood''s brazen and cold demeanor. He commands his brother''s military force and has established a firm hold on Northwind''s security.', 0),
(50761, 'Duke Johnathan Sherwood is known for his ruthless and efficient command over the city of Birkhaven and his own familial quarry in the northeast of Northwind. He does not tolerate failure and is quick to punish any injustices he sees. While this type of rule instills fear and anxiety in his subjects, one cannot deny the multitude of wealth his methods have accumulated.', 0),
(50762, 'Lady Josephine Mildenhall coordinates the agricultural aspects of Northwind. Both Crawford Winery and her own Mildenhall Horse Farm are important locations for the region''s economic growth. The patented Crawford Wine is an especially acquired taste and luxury good found within the banquet halls of any Stormwind noble. Lady Mildenhall''s kind and maternal nature makes her particularly cherished among the children of Ambershire.', 0),
(50763, 'In this month''s publication of The Greatest Minds of Azeroth, we''ll be taking a look at the shortest geniuses of the Eastern Kingdom! The adaptive and intelligent Gnomes of Khaz Modan are known for their groundbreaking creations, ranging from small, hand-held devices to earthquaking, mountable robo-suits!', 0),
(50764, 'We will take a closer look at the most renowned inventors the gnomish race has brought up over the last century! Both well-known and obscure virtuosos will be presented today, displaying their engineering feats to the wider audience.', 0),
(50765, 'Tinkmaster Overspark$B$BThe Discombobulator Ray is without a doubt Overspark''s magnum opus. This nifty little machine allows for simple - albeit very risky - transformation of living beings into harmless squirrels. When unveiling and demonstrating his grand creation, the masses were astonished by the level of ease with which the ray gun could be operated with. What they were not astonished by was the fact the test subject transformed into a vicious raptor shortly after assuming its new squirrel form. Luckily the wild beast could be subdued and no gnome was harmed in the process.', 0),
(50766, 'Oglethorpe Obnoticus$B$BMr Obnoticus was considered a genius even among the high council of tinkerers in Gnomeregan, yet after an unforeseen incident during a robot fighting competition, he was ostracized from the great city. While the actual course of events was never published, there are rumors saying Obnoticus was set up by a fellow inventor, misusing his harmless robot fighter blueprints to build a violent machine and putting the blame on him in the process. Following his exile, he settled in the port city of Booty Bay, from which he developed an autonomous sentry unit with the OOX series of battle chickens.', 0),
(50767, 'Sicco Thermaplugg$B$BA highly controversial topic, but one cannot deny Thermaplugg''s engineering prowess, as he was directly competing with Gelbin Mekkatorque for the election of High Tinkerer. With the creation of the fully operational Assault Gear, he ushered in a new age for gnomish warfare. Sadly it would not be used for the greater good of mankind, but instead for its own detriment.', 0),
(50768, 'Following the fallout of Gnomeregan, the blueprints for the Assault Gear had been lost in the ruins of the once great city. Other contributions of Thermaplugg were his work on the Gnomeregan Ventilation System, his cooperations with Gelbin Mekkatorque as well as a series of surprisingly well behaving mechanical dogs many gnomes lovingly called Scrappy.', 0),
(50769, 'Gelbin Mekkatorque$B$BA rising star in the past centuries of gnomish inventions, Mekkatorque is known for his diligent and intricate engineering work he perfected over the years following the establishment of his very own tinker emporium. Co-developing many astounding gadgets with his former friend Sicco Thermaplugg, Mekkatorque''s popularity skyrocketed with each new invention he brought to life.', 0),
(50770, 'Many of these found day-to-day applications like the Hair-o-Gain 3000, saving many gnomish men from early baldness. It did not take long for the gnomes to elect him as the High Tinkerer, the ruler of the gnomish people, given only to those deemed as the most intelligent and creative among the gnomes. Accepting the election with humility and gratitude, he vowed to uphold gnomish values and create more and more inventions to the betterment of not only the Gnomes, but also their newfound allies of the Alliance. An oath he values and honors to this day.', 0),
(50771, 'We have reached the end of this month''s iteration of The Greatest Minds of Azeroth! In our next publication we will take a look at the Tauren tribes of Kalimdor and the cultural differences they developed over the many years of their nomadic lifestyle.', 0),
(50772, 'Once upon a time, in the verdant fields of Northwind, there was a little girl by the name of Tiffany. She lived with her parents in the outskirts of the serene town of Ambershire, known for its perpetual fall of leaves. All of the children of Ambershire loved to play in the leaves piling up on the streets, and Tiffany was no different.', 0),
(50773, 'She was frolicking around the maple leaves with her friends Roderick and Karen, two rambunctious troublemakers. From throwing eggs at the bailiff to tying the shoelaces of innocent visitors together; many pranks were held, much to the schadenfreude of them both.', 0),
(50774, 'Tiffany was a timid girl, so while she got along very well with her friends, she never had the courage to accompany them on their pranking streaks - something both Roderick and Karen mocked her about. "You are a little chicken!", they said. "Maybe we should find a friend who is not so boring!" Words that hit poor little Tiffany very hard.', 0),
(50775, 'But Tiffany wouldn''t let that keep her down. For all the timidness she had, she possessed equal parts of bravado. When it was time for her friends to brew mischief again, she would not chicken out and accompany them instead - even though it was a really dangerous endeavour.', 0),
(50776, 'Their goal was as enigmatic as it was careless, had their parents not forbidden them to venture there. There were rumors about an old hag, living deep within the mountains of Northwind. People spoke about her in bad faith, associating her with all sorts of occult rituals and pagan practices. Some even said she devours animals during full moon nights to grant herself eternal youth! All of these rumors made it all the more appetizing for the three young and curious friends to try their luck in finding this mysterious witch of the woods.', 0),
(50777, 'One fateful night, the three of them snuck out to act on their plan. Nabbing a nearby lamp, they silently left Ambershire and followed its road to the edge of the forest where the witch was said to live. While Tiffany was clearly anxious and scared, there were no signs of any fear coming from Roderick and Karen.', 0),
(50778, 'Waltzing into the woods without a care in the world, both of them were cracking jokes and laughing at their parents for making up so many wild stories about this supposed witch. Tiffany tried to keep them quiet, but they were obviously not listening.', 0),
(50779, 'After a long walk through the pitch black forest, their lantern began to lose its light. Desperately trying to keep it alive, Karen was starting to panic, fearing she might be stuck in the woods on this moonless night. Roderick tried to snap her out of her tantrum, with little to no avail. It was at that moment, that Tiffany heard a rustling nearby, followed by a growl - a noise she heard before.', 0),
(50780, 'It was the growling of a bear, disturbed by all the commotion. Tiffany once went into the woods with her father to collect mushrooms, where they encountered such a beast. Mortified, her two panicking friends could not muster neither words nor strength to move. They had not been seen yet, so Tiffany took the chance and grabbed both of their hands! Holding on tightly, Roderick and Karen followed her through the undergrowth and shrubs, concealing their location.', 0),
(50781, 'They ran for what felt like an eternity and were completely out of breath and covered in mud and leaves. Still, their sudden escape - by some fortuitous stroke of luck - landed them at their initial destination: A gnarly and twisted house, illuminated with the welcoming red light of fire. This must be the witches'' house they were trying to find! Without second thought, the three of them rushed inside, to escape the night''s freezing cold.', 0),
(50782, 'The inside of the weirdly shaped house was positively strange. Bubbling vials, a big cauldron, animal skulls, garlands of herbs and animal parts decorated the interior. Near the chimney laid a scrangly looking cat of clearly old age. The children however did not care, as they were freezing and needed the warmth from the crackling fire. Curiously enough, the cat did not care for the new company and continued purring peacefully. What the children experienced here did not match at all with what their parents had told them about the place.', 0),
(50783, 'Having regained a healthy temperature, the three started exploring the house. Many of the intricacies they saw when entering looked even more strange when viewed up close. Scouring through the shelves and chests, they found all sorts of curious items. It was definitely a treasure trove of exciting things to find. Enjoying her little adventure thoroughly, Tiffany looked outside, noticing that it started to rain - and the light of a lantern approaching the house. Shocked, the girl alerted her friends who promptly hid inside a cabinet, while she herself hid behind a wardrobe.', 0),
(50784, 'Tiffany''s heart pounded in fear, as she observed the old wooden door creak open slowly. Dressed in a reddish brown robe, donning a large pointy red hat, an old woman entered the house, drenched in the rain from outside. A cold wind coursed through the open dorr, dimming the previously welcoming light into an ominous tone. Tiffany could neither see nor hear much of what happened at the entrance, yet she saw the woman notice the muddy trail they left behind, as well as the old cat welcoming her return. With a strenuous walk, the feline strutted to a cabinet and started scratching on its door - much to the shock of Tiffany. It was the cabinet her friends were hiding in!', 0),
(50785, 'Heavy footsteps of a vigorous walk echoed through the house, as the old woman rushed to the cabinet, flinging its doors open with force! Shrieking at the surprise, Roderick and Karen screamed in fear at the towering figure. They tried to run past her, but her firm grasp grabbed them at their collars! Squirming and flailing about, they screamed for help, but it was for naught. The witch had them captured. With both of them in hands, she stormed back outside into the rain, leaving Tiffany behind. Shocked at what just happened, the young girl was petrified. What just happened went by too quickly. But just as quickly, she found resolve - resolve to help her friends!', 0),
(50786, 'As if she''d been guided by something she didn''t know, she ran after them into the rainy forest. Up the hill in the distance, she could see them: At the edge of a pond with children still in hand, the witch knelt down into the grass and plunged both Roderick and Karen into the water! Horrified, Tiffany screamed at the top of her lungs, alerting the witch. Her gaze turned to the little girl and she started approaching her rapidly! Wanting to escape, Tiffany started running into the woods, yet her little legs did not take her far enough, making her trip into the mud. Turning around, the last she ever saw was the witches'' ugly, wart and scar-ridden face.', 0),
(50787, 'Our beloved queen, mother, wife and daughter$B$BYour radiance was as bright$Bas the Sun and just as warm$B$BOur hearts turned cold and heavy$B the day you were taken from us$B$BMay you find eternal rest$Bunder the rays of the Light$B$B- King Varian Wrynn', 0),
(50788, 'Praised are the courageous heroes$Bthat died in service of the Alliance$B$BDon’t forget their selfless sacrifices$Band remember what they stood for in life$B$B- Archbishop Benedictus', 0),
(50789, 'Trusted advisors to His Highness$BLoyal servants to the Kingdom$BTheir enlightened guidance led these$Blands to heights thought unreachable$B$B- High Sorcerer Andromath', 0),
(50790, 'Patron mother of Stormwind$BHer Light paved the way for her home to be reborn$BHer kind and compassionate nature gave comfort in times of peril$BMay she find eternal respite within the embrace of the Light$B$B- Archbishop Benedictus', 0),
(50791, 'Dearest adventurer, I hope you find my little game in good faith. Our fine Lady Selind is most assuredly distraught about her missing possession, but fret not. I will offer you a fair clue on where to find that which you seek.$B$BBeneath the plumpest orange you will see something that should not be there.', 0),
(50792, 'Bravo! You''ve taken your first successful step in solving my riddle. I must say, seeing you rummage through that pumpkin field was amusing. Did you know that your client also likes to rummage through stuff; namely other people''s affairs? Enticing, isn''t it? Nevertheless, a new clue for my aspiring treasure hunter.$B$BA lonely home caught in icy breezes, a hollow chest of freezing iron.', 0),
(50793, 'Quite chilly up here, don''t you think? No worries, dearest friend, I am properly coated against any uncomfortable cold. Speaking of uncomfortable: Lady Selind is awfully cold herself. You can''t really blame her can you? Her nobleness is just too divine for the common man to understand. If only she could do something about it! Enough of her, back to you and my fascinating game. This one is a bit more tricky, but nothing is too hard for you, is it?$B$BA vacant lookout over the cerulean depths.', 0),
(50794, 'A lovely view, wouldn''t you agree? I am sure Lady Selind would concur. If she had any sense of beauty in her heart. But alas, a foul person such as herself wouldn''t comprehend it if it was right in front of her. She will soon enough comprehend how fragile her life truly is. Forgive me, don''t panic. I wouldn''t dare hurt anyone, it would simply be too ugly. We''re here for a fun game after all, and almost at the end! I had such tremendous fun watching you wander around Northwind, I should definitely do this again very soon. Till then, best of luck on your ventures, dearest friend. Here is the final clue.$B$BUnder the dragon''s claws golden luck awaits. ~ Phantom Thief C.', 0),
(50795, 'Ambershire is normally heavily guarded, but the Jousting Tournament and recent attacks by the orcs and Dark Iron present a ripe opportunity for us. This is our moment to strike!', 0),
(50796, 'Use the cover of the night to ascertain the situation and learn the guard''s patrols. Once you memorize them and ONLY then, return to our base up at Crystal Falls to the southeast, and make sure not to get caught by the folk from the inn at Grimmen Lake!', 0),
(50797, 'Paddley, our operations in Westfall are reaching their peak. The golem production is steady and virtually flawless, Voss'' experiments with our secret biological component are fruitful as well. Despite this, it is in our best interest to make haste - Shaw and his lackeys are on the move and I cannot have them interfere with our cause.', 0),
(50798, 'While a few of our men are scouring the abandoned farms of Duskwood, I need you and your subordinates to plunder the filthy nobles of Northwind. Make this a hasty operation, Paddley. Clean and merciless. The fat and indolent wretches don''t deserve anything, so gut them if need be. Leave no witnesses. I expect steady reports, our contractors from the Venture Co. are neither patient nor cheap.', 0),
(50799, 'Your initiative to expand into the bordering lands of Northwind proved to be a complete success, Bragordi! These new gnoll slaves you have brought with you are doing excellent work in the Slag Pit; resilient, pain resistant and most of all: They know how to use those muscles! Compared to the human and Bronzebeard slaves crying for mercy and whatnot, they are much more efficient and pushed productivity tenfold!', 0),
(50800, 'If I remember correctly, you have set your eyes on the local kobolds and already started putting some of them to work. Should their natural affinity to digging prove useful, ship them directly to the Searing Gorge. I don''t need any more humans of the sort, I''ve grown a liking to these critters and their animalistic strength! I expect steady reports from you.$B$BFor the Glory of Ragnaros - Overseer Maltorius', 0),
(50801, 'These weak humans are pathetic, barely worth the effort! Their measly defenses were easily destroyed by the Blackrock''s mighty power. Now with this watchtower in our control, our assault on the occupied quarry can begin. Our warchief demands us to crush the infantile minions of Ragnaros and establish a foothold in these lands to ultimately snuff out their lives beneath our feet.', 0),
(50802, 'Shuni, fortify your position on the watchtower and crush any foolish enough to mount an attack. Leave no survivors, the might of Blackrock knows no mercy!', 0),
(50803, 'The dust settled as the sky frowned its mighty grey clouds upon the battlefield, yet no drop of rain ever fell. Somehow, though, for my soul it felt like raining—as tears fell from my eyes, watching my comrades fall one after the other. Even when the cruelty of this world was at its peak, the sky did not weep, so I had to.$B$BWe were young boys, young boys coming to defend our land and people in a war not waged by us, a fire we did not start. Yet those who guided us to this forsaken land kept it ablaze, and it was the corpses of my brothers-in-arms that fed its flames.', 0),
(50804, 'I am at a crossroads. We are so few left, and though the enemy themselves have lost many, they are still far more vicious and bloodthirsty than we are. So what hope is there, where hundreds have fallen for mere dozens to succeed? I fear this letter will never reach you, Mother and Father; it will never feel the warm morning breeze sweeping over the pond next to our home. The fool I was, the fool I still am, for dreaming of tasting food from your hands again, Mother, or enjoying a pint of Amberale after a hard day''s labor, Father.', 0),
(50805, 'I lie now in this ragged tent, surrounded by wounded men who are already dead—yet still they walk, still they fight, still they hope for tomorrow to come. We are outnumbered and outmatched. Hope is a foolish ambition for those sent to fight a losing battle. I doubt we will succeed.', 0),
(50806, 'Yet, somehow, by some means, just as the flames of war still burn, so does my fighting spirit. I do not wish to cower before death; I do not wish to meet my end with fear. It all ends with this next attack. I truly hope the skies will weep for us in the end. And as I lie among the corpses of my brethren, in the mud and muck, I want to feel the eternal sunlight one last time—to brush my face with its kind touch, just as you used to.', 0),
(50807, 'Should this letter ever reach your hands, dear Mother and Father, I hope some comfort reaches you as well. The comfort that, though I lost my life carrying the banner of my land and the wills of my people, I did not fear death. I accepted it. May we once again meet in the lands beyond, blinded by the Light, hand in hand, as we once greeted the sunrise together before a day of labor.$B$BWith eternal love, your son.', 0),
(50808, 'YYeast and Simple Flour from Ulrich Buckert.$B$BHoney and Sparkling Water from Thomas Arello.', 0),
(50809, 'These records tell the tale of a valiant knight, his humble beginnings and his heroic deeds in the service of our kingdom. Inspiring many young squires with his legacy, Sir Vellas'' story acts as a beacon on what a true Stormwind knight ought to be - fearless, chivalrous and compassionate.', 0),
(50810, 'Born the son of a simple farmer, Edrin lived an unremarkable life with his father on the edge of the forest of Elwynn. Most of his time was spent assisting him on the fields, planting the crops, caring for the ox carrying the tiller and feeding the countless hens that scurried around their home. When visiting the town of Goldshire to sell their wares, he caught glimpses of what the world outside of his ordinary home could be. Merchants with wares from far away, dazzling in the summer sun; knights of Stormwind in their prideful armor, donning the powerful lion of King Barathen. This part of the world, so far and yet so close, fascinated him dearly.', 0),
(50811, 'His father had long battled with a grievous sickness taking its toll on his health. One fateful day, he broke down on the field, coughing blood and sweating heavily. Edrin rushed to bring him to bed, as he had done many times before. Fighting the disease, he tasked his son to pick their remaining silver and seek the priests of Northshire Abbey for help. Promising his father he''d return with help, the young man ran as fast as he could to the northern abbey.', 0),
(50812, 'Arriving at Northshire Abbey, the forest had already been drenched in heavy rainfall and night began to fall. Knocking on the grand wooden doors of the stone building, Edrin pleaded for their help, yelling against the rain drowning out his voice. After minutes upon minutes of knocking, the doors finally opened. A guard with a lantern in his hand stood before him, a disgruntled look upon his face. Edrin tried again to ask for someone to help his ailing father, but the guard just scoffed at the young man. Telling him to stop pestering the priests at such a late hour, the guardsman shoved Edrin aside, making him fall into the puddled water before closing the door on him.', 0),
(50813, 'Bewildered and agape, Edrin raised himself from the dirty water. The abbey would not help him and his father. As despair slowly crept upon his heart, he fervently thought of ways to aid his father still. There had to be someone, something - that could rescue him from his sickness. Edrin was agitated as he ran back to Goldshire in hope of finding a kind soul. The town was mostly empty, with many people hiding from the rain inside their houses or the inn. Only one merchant remained on the town square, putting the last of his wares onto his wagon: potions and vials. Rarely were there ever alchemists visiting Goldshire, this must''ve been Edrin''s stroke of good fortune.', 0),
(50814, 'Edrin didn''t hesitate asking the merchant for help, telling him of the symptoms of his father''s ailment. Irritated and confused, the old merchant stopped the young man from falling over his own words, making him repeat his plea once more. Listening to the desperation in his voice, the merchant pondered. Losing more and more time, Edrin begged him for his aid, offering all the silver he had on him. It was clear to the old man that the farmer''s son was in bitter need of assistance. Although hesitant at first, the tradesman opened one of his crates and procured a deeply red vial from it. It would be Edrin''s in exchange for all the silver that he had.', 0),
(50815, 'With potion in hand, the run through the darkened forest became increasingly difficult. Elwynn was barely illuminated by the moonlight breaking through the clouds of rain; thanks to knowing his way home by heart Edrin was able to return home safely. Drenched and full of dirt, he rushed upstairs to his father''s bed. The candle he had placed before leaving was just short of burning out. His father was breathing erratically, his skin cold and sweat had stained the bed sheets. Full of panic and shock, Edrin poured the potion into his father''s mouth. The liquid gathered and spilled to the side of his mouth; before long Edrin realized that not even the potion could save his father anymore.', 0),
(50816, 'The sun stood at its highest peak as the young farmer laid the shovel against the oak tree just outside the farmstead. After hours of strenuous shoveling, Edrin had finished digging his father''s final resting place, just next to his late wife. Still in shock and disbelief, he continued doing what he had known best - tending to the farm. He tried his best to do his father justice, but it was clear the work was simply too much for a young man all alone. He managed to come by for a few days, before giving up on his cherished home. Releasing all the animals into the forest, Edrin gathered anything of value and headed to Goldshire.', 0),
(50817, 'The market was bustling as usual, the merchants yelled at the top of their lungs, trying to garner the attention of the townsfolk. It was Edrin''s plan to sell the few valuable things he brought with him; but none of the tradesmen even batted an eye to him. He recognized none of the tradesmen, so he tried his luck with a peddler with barely any customers. Greeting the young man, the hunched over huckster asked him to present what goods he had to sell. A candelabra,  some silverware and his father''s old sword is all Edrin had to offer. The merchant threw a frosty gaze upon his wares and with a disapproving gesture told him his junk is worth barely any silver, let alone copper.', 0),
(50818, 'Edrin was hurt and insulted by the scrawny merchant''s words, flouting the remaining keepsakes from his home. Either way, if he wanted to sleep in a warm bed at the inn, he had to get some money; it was doubtful he would have any more luck with the other peddlers. Reluctantly, he unsheathed the sword and placed it on the counter. However, before the merchant could even think of grabbing anything, he was interrupted by a deep and dominating voice, followed by a gauntlet pressing down on the sword''s blade. Edrin looked up in surprise, only to see a cloaked man, clad in armor underneath. Meeting the young man''s gaze, he told him that a true knight never sells his sword.', 0),
(50819, 'Intimidated by the imposing figure, the sniveling peddler simply bought Edrin''s other wares, giving a few silver coins instead. Thanking the good man, the armored knight took the sword and handed it back to Edrin. As quickly as he appeared did he leave. Still bewildered, Edrin threw a glance at the man, pondering about what just happened. The rugged hilt of the old sword left a rough feeling on his palm. Meeting such a man was no coincidence. A chance encounter of good fortune? Gripping the sword tightly, Edrin followed the knight to the road leading out of Goldshire.', 0),
(50820, 'Two years have passed since the fateful meeting between the lonesome farmer Edrin Vellas and the enigmatic warrior in Goldshire, who stopped the boy from selling his father''s sword. The old man was Wolram Notleigh, and he introduced himself as a wandering knight. Once in service of a wealthy and influential noble, he fell from grace after disobeying a direct order from his liege. An act that would violate his honor as a knight would never be carried out by him. Hardened faith in justice itself is what a Stormwind knight ought to strive for. This was Sir Notleigh''s dogma, one he would live and die for.', 0),
(50821, 'The veteran knight was of old age and had searched for a squire who would continue his legacy of justice and compassion. There has been too much ugliness in the kingdom that he alone would not be able to vanquish. On their chance encounter two years ago, Wolram recognized that very spirit in Edrin that he himself had learned to grow over his many years on Azeroth. A promising youth of good build and strength, and an iron will to survive.', 0),
(50822, 'It was just a few weeks after meeting that Edrin had started his training with Wolram in the martial arts and the virtues of knighthood. Years of work on his father''s field had given the young man rigorous strength and plentiful stamina, with which he performed Wolram''s exercises with diligence and perseverance. The physical side of knighthood was not the only thing he was instructed in. Many lessons on the etiquette and cordial behavior befitting a knight caused many a restless night for the eager student of lowly birth. It took him many months, but Edrin eventually settled into the role of Wolram''s squire fully. Soon, his training would be put to the test.', 0),
(50823, 'Wolram and Edrin had managed to survive and earn coin by offering their knightly services to those in need. Errands, finding missing people or acting as guards were just a few of the many jobs they were taking to cover their expenses. However, these deeds were done first and foremost for the betterment of the kingdom, to aid those in need and abandoned by hope.', 0),
(50824, 'It was one such job that would mark a significant moment in the relationship between Edrin and his master, a decisive turning point in both of their lives.', 0),
(50825, 'The two knights had returned to Goldshire after aiding a farmer in Westfall against a rabid pack of coyotes terrorizing his farmstead. Enjoying their reward - plentiful of the farmer''s local produce as well as a delicious Goretusk Liver Pie - they indulged in the delicacies on a wooden bench on the town square. Wolram congratulated Edrin on his masterful display of tracking down the coyotes, something he had been taught by his father when he was just a boy. Thanking his master, the squire paid him right back, by thanking him for his latest posture training, which proved to be pivotal in their fight against the wild animals. Wolram gave his squire a friendly push on the shoulder.', 0),
(50826, 'While they ate and regained their strength after the long travel, a group of priests from Northshire Abbey, accompanied by a handful of guards and a carriage, traversed the town square in a rigid formation. Citizens and merchants alike stepped aside to make way for the esteemed clerics and their entourage. Observing the spectacle, Wolram passed his student his ration and approached their abbot, a lavishly dressed man, who held a watchful eye over the ornate chest secured on the wagon he was sitting on. Edrin was unable to hear what the two were conversing about, just that the guards closed in on the old knight, prepared to protect the abbot.', 0),
(50827, 'Thanks to Wolram''s charismatic abilities however, the situation was quickly diffused and with a swift hand motion he ordered his squire to join him at the carriage. Edrin asked his master what the matter was, to which he replied that they''ve got new work already. Hesitant at the prospect, the squire gathered their belongings and accompanied Wolram at the wagon. Their mission was simple: Guard the clerics and their cargo on their way to Grand Hamlet in the southern Elwynn Forest. In Edrin''s eyes, a simple enough job,  nothing they hadn''t done before. The young man greeted his employers cordially before marching close to his master.', 0),
(50828, 'The carriage''s horses trotted at a slow speed, giving Edrin ample time to check his surroundings and company. Four priests, their abbot and four guards were all that the abbey had sent to deliver their mysterious freight. Edrin felt uneasy just being near them and intently observed each one of the guardsmen. Regular men of middle age and well-armed with swords and shields. One looking bored out of his mind, the other marching in an earnest motion, while the third was unremarkable. Taking a look at the fourth guard behind him, a sharp pain pierced Edrin''s chest. What he saw was the face of the one he''d never forget. He recognized the man he had last seen two years ago.', 0),
(50829, 'Wolram noticed his squire''s unrest, the nervous playing with the hilt of his sword became more and more apparent. Confiding in him, he asked what plagued his heart so much. It was difficult for the young man to speak those words of weakness to his master, but he reluctantly answered him. About his feelings of hate, rage and the dark thoughts that had followed him in his nightmares ever since he lost his father. Edrin had opened up to Wolram many times before, albeit taking some time at first, but he never spoke about the feelings he harbored for the man he made responsible for the death of his father. Laying his hand on his shoulder, Wolfram urged his squire to quell his emotions.', 0),
(50830, 'Hours had passed and the sun began to set. The caravan had traveled through most of Elwynn Forest and was just leaving the Redridge Mountains on the last stretches to Grand Hamlet. Worn down from the long travel, the guardsmen were already speaking of the famed ice cold ale of the Scarlet Raven Tavern and their homemade apple tartes. Wolram on the other hand was still on high alert, with Edrin trying his best to follow his example, even though the laughter of the guards irritated him greatly. He tried to focus on the sound of the horses'' horseshoes hitting the paved way, finding any way of blocking out the rabble would be enough for him.', 0),
(50831, 'Edrin''s focus was broken by a loud crack from above the ravine they were traspessing. Swords at hand, they steered in the direction of the noise, only to see a huge log crashing down the cliffside. Managing to narrowly escape the massive tree, it landed with a deafening smash on the wagon, flinging the chest and two of the priests and their abbot off of it. Startled by the commotion, the horses reared up, breaking from their reins and darting into the woods. Chaos ensued, Wolram and Edrin had barely any time to assess the situation, as they needed to defend themselves. A group of bandits ambushed their caravan. Their goal was the gold coins inside the chest, now scattered on the ground.', 0),
(50832, 'The clashing of metal was loud and ubiquitous. Two of the guards had already fallen to the ambush, one crushed beneath the tree, the other succumbing to two of the five bandits. Wolram ensured the clerics were escaping the battlefield towards Grand Hamlet, while he and the third guard were fending off the brigands. Edrin was fighting two of them at once, but as fortune was on his side, they were not of equal talent. What must''ve been a new recruit was easily dealt with by a few slashes with his sword, bringing him quickly to the ground. Fighting two enemies at once was not easy for Edrin, but two lowly outlaws were no match for the trained squire.', 0),
(50833, 'Finishing his second duel with a quick stab, Edrin finally had room to breathe. He turned to his master who had been helping the injured guard beyond the fallen tree. Explaining that the gold had been stolen by the last remaining thief, Wolram told his student to follow the fourth guard that had given chase after the bandit. Begrudgingly, the squire nodded and made haste, tracking both of them down. Running through the brush of the forest, their trail was not hard to spot. Rustled leaves and churned up earth made it easy for the farm boy to find them. Edrin followed their trail for a short while, before it abruptly ended near a short cliff.', 0),
(50834, 'Looking down, he spotted two bodies piled up within the ravine, the chest filled with gold closeby. Blood was smeared across the rocks, it seemed that both of them fell down during the skirmish, into their demise. Edrin cautiously descended the rugged cliff to retrieve the chest, when he heard a noise come from the two men. The guard had survived the fall, but broken his arm on impact. Pleading for help, he reached towards Edrin in desperation. Edrin, however, simply stared in silent contemptment. It was the same man he had begged for help that fateful night, who is now doing the same. Crying and whimpering at the young man, the guard asked again, but Edrin would have none of it.', 0),
(50835, 'During his time of need, this man dismissed a young boy searching for someone who could save his father. His apathy had cost the life of a loved one. This would be his retribution. The answer for his grave misdeed. The squire picked up the chest and heaved it up the cliff. Shocked and horrified, the guard''s desperation grew even greater, but Edrin ignored all of it. For him, this man had doomed himself two years ago and this was his fate. Returning to Wolram, exhausted from pulling the chest through the forest, he lied to his master, telling him both guard and bandit died from the fall. The knight spoke his prayers to the guard, before aiding Edrin in bringing the cargo to Grand Hamlet.', 0),
(50836, 'Two guardsmen and a cleric had lost their lives that day. Despite the unexpected ambush, both the abbot and the chest made it safely to Grand Hamlet, for which the knight and his squire had been compensated. They stayed in town, but Edrin was restless for the next few days. Wolram noticed the state his student was in and eventually joined him on the bench outside the tavern he would sit on each night. Torn about his actions, Edrin ultimately released his anger and confessed his lie to Wolram. How seeing this man, this monster in such pain made him feel vindicated. How it made him feel powerful. That he deserved it all for what he had done.', 0),
(50837, 'Wolram stood up and with an angered, disciplined look scolded his student harshly for his misconduct of the sworn oath he pledged when becoming his squire. What he had done was inexcusable and not befitting of someone he had considered his successor. Still emotional, Edrin shouted at his master, in an attempt to make him understand. But Wolram understood from the beginning. Stopping the young man''s tirades with his deep voice, the knight spoke his final word. He absolved him from his duties as his squire, denying him the right to train under him any longer. Feeling hurt and miserable, Edrin struggled to find clear thoughts. In the end, he accepted and left. Without saying a word.', 0),
(50838, 'The inn was filled with visitors enjoying food and drink. Men and women alike were hiding from the heavy downpour that had riddled Northwind for a good while. In spite of that, moods were not dampened as the alcohol was poured in excess to keep the spirits high. A group of women were sitting next to the fireplace, warming themselves up from the cold evening. Chatting with each other gleefully, they garnered the attention of a drunk lumberjack from across the room, waddling towards them. His attempts at being suave were not so successful, as he burped and stammered them out more than anything. The fine ladies were getting visibly annoyed by their unwanted guest, much to his dismay.', 0),
(50839, 'Irritated at the rejection, the lumberjack began arguing with the ones he wanted to woo at first. Neither side wanted to let go and emotions welled up quickly. The other guests started watching the spectacle and the innkeeper tried to calm them down, but to no avail. Both side''s temper had reached a critical point and a brawl was about to break out. But before any punches could''ve been thrown, an imposing cloaked figure stepped in between the fighting parties. His armored gauntlets pushing them aside, the man implored them to simply enjoy the night and festivities. They scoffed at him and begrudgingly returned to their tables. He himself sighed and followed suit.', 0),
(50840, 'Rubbing his stubbled jaw, the knight leaned back into his chair in the corner of the room, relieved he could prevent unnecessary violence. Exhaustion had caught up to him after the long journey to Ambershire. All he wanted was a cold ale to end the day with. Fortunately for him, the innkeeper wanted to thank him for his aid and brought him a specialty mug filled with his finest ale. Appreciating the gesture, the knight played down his efforts, saying anyone could have done the same. The innkeeper laughed and toasted to his honored guest. Before leaving him to his vices, he asked the cloaked man for his name. With reluctance, the knight answered: Edrin Vellas, Wanderer.', 0),
(50841, 'Edrin left his room the next morning before sunrise. He had come to Ambershire for work, and had hoped that the wealthy people of Northwind would be in need of a pair of strong arms. Many of the resident lord''s soldiers had been conscripted to liberate the island of Balor of intruders; at least that''s what Edrin had heard through the grapevine. It did not take long for the wanderer to find work. A farmer had trouble caring sufficiently for his horses, something Edrin was not shy of doing. While he didn''t really tend to horses before, Wolram had told him about the basics on how to properly handle a horse before, one of the many lessons in knighthood the young man took to heart.', 0),
(50842, 'Finishing up, the day had already advanced to the afternoon. Rewarded with food and coin, Edrin made his way to Stillheart Port. On his way he got past the famed Jousting Grounds of Lord Amberwood and Amberwood Keep itself. Laying his eyes upon the tournament tribunals, he imagined what it would feel like to be cheered on by the fascinated spectators. With a bittersweet chuckle, Edrin shook his head and continued onwards. The sky darkened, and he could tell by the patteing sounds on his heavy armor that rain had begun to fall once more.', 0),
(50843, 'For the next few days, Edrin had been a blessing for the people of Northwind. His fighting prowess, endurance and wit were valuable assets in aiding them wherever he could. Regardless of the complexity of the task, the wandering youth gave it his all to help those in need to the best of his abilities. Edrin was on his way back to the inn for a good night''s rest, when night had fallen. The hills of Northwind were quiet except for an eerie howl racing throught the auburn trees. Letting his mind wander through the depth of night, Edrin looked up at the sky, reminiscing of the past. More than a year had passed since Wolram absconded him as his squire, and he hadn''t seen him since.', 0),
(50844, 'He wandered the kingdom, living from hand to mouth. Taking the occasional job, still adhering to the dogma Wolram had taught him, even without his guidance. He wondered where he''d be now. Edrin''s thoughts were cut short by terrified screaming. Searching the parameter, he noticed a small cottage off to the road, just a sprint away. He readied his blade and approached the house carefully, wastin no time. Coming closer, the young knight heard the clashing of steel and the audible exhaustion between the two fighters. Two men, it seemed. The cries he heard first now turned out to be that of women, two atleast. Whatever happened inside, Edrin had little time to act.', 0),
(50845, 'A blood curdling scream of pain echoed through the night, followed by more female screams. The time to think was cut short and Edrin rushed to the cottage''s door, flinging it open. The scene was hectic still, on one side a mother and her daughter, hysterically crying in the corner of the room. Opposite of them, a tall man with a bent arm and bloodied sword in hand. On the ground, an armored man, motionless. Edrin didn''t have time to recollect all the information; but it was clear that he interrupted a robbery. The bandit turned towards the noise of the door and yelled at Edrin with wrathful eyes. He knew the young man, and after a few seconds, he would remember as well.', 0),
(50846, 'The intruder in front of Edrin was none other than the guard he left to die during the escort job to Grand Hamlet. He had survived his injuries and seemingly turned to banditry afterwards. The misery inflicted upon him had not been forgotten, a feeling Edrin could very well relate to. Pooling all of his anger and frustration into his sword, the bandit charged at his opponent who blocked the powerful strike. It was obvious that he was a trained Stormwind guard, since his swordblows were precise and deadly. Edrin has trouble deflecting the sword, as he was both exhausted and caught off-guard by the bandit''s sudden burst of violence. He had to switch to the offensive, quickly.', 0),
(50847, 'Putting the brigand into a lock with their weapons, Edrin grabbed the blade of his sword and hit his enemy''s head with the pummel of its hilt. Taken aback by the abrupt force, he stumbled backwards, giving Edrin enough time to follow up with a upwards slash across his chest, ending his life. Now two corpses laid on the ground, soaking it with even more blood. The mother and her daughter were still in shock and whimpered in their corner, clearly drained of energy. Edrin tried to catch his breath; he wasn''t at his best after the hard day of work. Kneeling next to the robber, he made sure he was dealt with; and to his relief, he was no longer posing a threat.', 0),
(50848, 'The knight sheathed his sword and turned to the women, assuring them that they were in danger no more. Nevertheless, they were still too caught up in their distress to be responsive. Edrin on the other hand was somewhat comforted by them calming down at least a little bit. With the situation under control, he turned his attention to the enigmatic armored man, who fought the bandit beforehand. The knight got close enough to see his face, and when he did, his heart skipped a beat. The corpse lying before him was Wolram, his old mentor. Bewildered, Edrin immediately picked him up against the wall, but there was no way of saving him anymore. The book on Wolram Notleigh''s life closed that night.', 0),
(50849, 'Emotions raced inside Edrin. Anger, grief, guilt, confusion. How could this have happened? Was this the retribution for his own selfish desire for revenge on the man he didn''t even know the name of? The man who was unaware of the reason for his actions? Countless questions swirled inside his mind, one more condemning than the other. But in the end, no answer could soothe his conflicted soul. His doings caused this, and no matter how much he would try to deny it: It was the unshakeable truth. Regardless, he had others to take care of. Wiping away his tears, Edrin helped the two women up. Carrying the girl on his arm, he led them to the inn near Ambershire.', 0),
(50850, 'The next day, Edrin went to Amberwood Keep to inform its residents of last night''s happenings. From what the rescued mother had told him, she and her daughter welcomed Wolram into their home, as he needed to rest for the night. When they were attacked by the bandit, the old knight tried to defend them, but his old age had caught up to him, giving his enemy the lethal advantage. She said that Wolram was looking for someone, but Edrin quickly abandoned that thought. It was easier for him to not assume it to be the case, or else the guilt would''ve devoured him from within. Edrin explained to the Amberwood guards what had happened and accompanied them in retrieving the corpses.', 0),
(50851, 'The thief was given a quick burial in an unnamed grave, whereas Wolram was laid to rest at his family''s estate near Stormwind. Back in Ambershire, Edrin recalled last night''s events; being confronted with the consequences of his actions was devastating for the young man. With his head hanging low, he was approached by one of the guards he had assisted earlier. Edrin had drawn quite a lot of attention to him, so much that Lord Amberwood himself wanted to speak with him. Unable to refuse a noble''s request, he nodded and followed the guard.', 0),
(50852, 'Amberwood Keep was grand and imposing, worthy of the ruler of Northwind. Soon they reached the throne room and both of them bowed before the lord.', 0),
(50853, 'Lord Amberwood spoke of Edrin''s helpfulness with his subjects, and expressed his gratitude for his aid. Furthermore, he thanked him deeply for avenging the death of Sir Notleigh, his favoured knight. Edrin was surprised. The noble Wolram had been in service was Lord Amberwood himself. Even after his disobedience, the noble still spoke highly of him. Relieved, Edrin explained to him how Wolram had wished for him to continue his legacy as an honorable knight, but that he had doubts he''d ever achieve that. The lord denied his foolish notion with a chuckle, reassuring him there''d be no need for scepticism. Instead, he offered him a spot among his knights, leaving young Edrin speechless.', 0),
(50854, 'From then on out, Edrin would grow in strength, mind and soul. His noble deeds of heroism and valiance would be remembered not only among the citizens of Northwind, but the whole kingdom. The simple farmer''s son, who had faced countless hardships and regret in his life rose up to become a symbol of knighthood. The virtues he and his master stood for paved the way for all knights and squires following in their footsteps.', 0),
(50855, 'Here lies Sir Wolram Notleigh,$Bson of Vergil Notleigh, noble of Northwind.$B$BA beacon of virtue, his sacrifices in service of the kingdom will not be forgotten.$B$BMay his final rest be left undisturbed.$B$B- Sir Edrin Vellas', 0),
(50856, 'To my most trusted friend Medivh,$B$B$B$BIt has been too long since we last met. I hope this letter finds you in good health. Our last meeting did not end as it should have, and I regret the distance that has grown between us. Must you truly remain alone atop your tower?$B$BWere it not for Moroes, I would fear you lost. You have become so distant, my friend—so distant that I wonder if you even read my letters. Yet this message bears great importance.$B$BThe Light has blessed my family with an heir. My son has been born, a beacon of hope for Stormwind. I beg you—leave your tower, meet him, hold him, and celebrate with me. It is my deepest wish that you grant him a name.$B$BYour absence weighs heavy on my heart, yet I believe you would not forsake me. Come, my friend, and let us mend what has been lost.$B$B$BYour king and friend,$BLlane Wrynn.', 0),
(50857, 'It cannot be explained. This thing—this twisted, cold amalgamation of pure evil. I have read almost every book in my library, yet I have found no answer. Could Karazhan truly hold no information on this alien thing? No, I must not lose composure. I need to keep going.', 0),
(50858, 'I hear it whisper its name, even from the dark, deep vaults I have locked it in. It calls itself ''Arc''Tiras,'' and ever since the moment I touched it, my mind has raced with questions—questions I have yet to answer. It feels cold, yet twisted and dark, as if it has a will of its own.', 0),
(50859, 'With time, it will grow weaker. The vaults will keep it under control—or so I hope. Otherwise, the whole city will freeze at its will. I have stumbled upon a book from the elven lands of Quel''Thalas. It speaks of a distant continent, one from which they originated. Though I am accustomed to their tongue, this feels more archaic. I feel I am getting closer.', 0),
(50860, 'It is still rough around the edges, but I have managed to start a translation. I feel dejected… Whatever this other land to the west may be, I had no knowledge of it, nor did I ever question its existence before. Have I grown too comfortable in my role as Guardian?', 0),
(50861, 'I am soon to travel to Silvermoon. I must find someone who can translate this bit by bit. I hope they will not turn me away as they have on more than one occasion. Though they were the ones to teach us magic, they still keep some knowledge to themselves—especially from someone they see as a threat.', 0),
(50862, '<Many of the pages have eroded over time, and what is intelligible is covered with a thick layer of dust.>', 0),
(50863, '...and it was at the mercy of the Light, that we are gathered here, in holy communion. Our faith in its magnificence saved us from the horrors of the lowly heathens who plundered our home; saved our revered duke from a watery grave and blessed us with our perennial wealth. It is imperative for us to stay true in our belief of the Light, so that our diligence and devotion may be rewarded. So let us once again convene in silent prayer; express your humility to the radiant...', 0),
(50864, '...in the sea we trust; in hallowed trade we trust; in the divine Light we trust; may it deliver its radiance upon us, its humble servants. Now, rise, children of the Light and bathe in its benevolent rays. Embrace the...$B$B<You cannot decipher the rest; it''d be best to hand it to Noppsy.>', 0),
(50865, 'I fear for his dukeship''s health. It has been ten days since we''ve found him on our shores after his vessel has breached in that devastating storm. Nothing short of a miracle he survived the raging tides, yet his current condition isn''t any better. He is delirious and mumbles about some sort of seahorse that had carried him to safety on his back. I requested urgent help from Stormwind City''s priests, but it will take a few more days till they arrive.', 0),
(50866, 'My logical thinking forbids me to believe my duke''s feverish ramblings, yet there is no possibility for him to have outlived the sea that far from Balor. This seahorse... I''ve never heard of anything like it. Kelpie, he calls it. If what he is saying is truly factual, then it is my obligation as his adjutant to investigate this strange phenomenon. I will send a messenger to Kul Tiras posthaste, if I am to find any clues about this mythical sea creature, it has to be there.', 0),
(50867, '<The rest of the pages are too damaged for you to read.>', 0),
(50868, '<The book is riddled with dried up stains of unknown liquids.>', 0),
(50869, '...they can kiss my arse, for all I care! I knew what I saw and I''m telling you, it was the real deal! The shiny scales, the long flowing mane...! It was all there, mere yards aways from me. It was just like my mother used to describe it, so I know it to be true. Sure, I was drunk that night, but my eyes don''t betray me, even after the tenth mug of ale. The kelp-like mane, fishy tail and neighing can only mean one thing! Mother''s stories were true all along!', 0),
(50870, '<The next pages are either torn or unintelligible.>', 0),
(50871, 'Dathronag the Mighty was a fearsome and heroic warrior. His actions have single-handedly saved the lower halls of our city. From the great demon incursions of the discovery, to the terrible beasts that lurked in the deep tunnels. His sacrifice in defeating the blazing demon ''Kress'' has given us the chance to live in peace once again.$B$BMay his memory be everlasting, and may his gaze be an inspiration to all that work in the lower reserve.', 0),
(50872, 'Algoron the Uniter was a true diplomat, and gifted sorcerer. It is his actions that united the lesser dwarven clans within Grim Batol and ended the second separation. Algoron gave his life in defense of Grim Batol, and fought alongside fellow soldiers in the lower reserve during the great demon incursion. His death has given us the wisdom to understand the strength in unity. May his knowledge and heart live within all dwarves.', 0),
(50873, 'This memorial is dedicated to the many brave miners who lost their lives during the great demon incursion. Their demise shall never be forgotten, and their bravery will always be commended for facing such a terrible evil.', 0),
(50874, 'As Modgud fell, the tide of assault shattered like brittle stone, and the order to retreat thundered through the halls. Yet many of our kin, lost in the labyrinthine depths of Grim Batol—blinded by rage and lust—were caught too deep to heed the call. The shadows, thick and ancient, rose from Modgud''s fallen corpse and swallowed them whole. $B$BI saw them. I saw my brothers—once stout and proud—down on the lower floors, consumed by darkness that no light dared touch. $B$BI heard them. Oh, how I heard them—their screams of torment twisted by the curse of shadow, their voices torn from their very souls as they were no longer dwarves, but twisted shadows of flesh.', 0),
(50875, 'No time was granted to linger, for we fled with every ounce of breath and steel, pursued by those blasted Wildhammer fools and the creeping darkness alike. But the horror I glimpsed that day haunts my nights still. $B$BThese were no kin. No. What they became was a blasphemy upon the Makers'' craft, a mockery of all that a dwarf stands for. $B$BThe skardyn, they call them now. Cursed souls, once our brothers and sisters. And what did we do? We left them to rot in that accursed place, condemned to suffer in shadow.', 0),
(50876, 'Long years passed after that cursed battle, before the Red Dragonflight came, their cleansing flames purging what remained. The few skardyn that dared linger in the light were burned to ash, or so the tales tell...', 0),
(50877, 'In honor of our savior, the brave and fearless woman who defended her home with unparalleled courage.$B$BWere it not for her selfless deeds in times of peril and turmoil, we would not stand here commemorating her heroic sacrifice.$B$BMay your name be forever whispered among the cliffs of Balor.$B$B- Lord Victor Grahan', 0),
(50878, 'By Storm, Earth, and Fire - our races have been united and returned the Horde to its shamanistic roots. This stone stands as a testament to our unity and as a memorial to those who fell protecting it.', 0),
(50879, 'A shrine dedicated to those that fought, and gave their lives in the defense of innocents against our greatest of challenges. May this shrine forever honor those that died within our once great halls in defiance against our invaders.$B$BYou shall never be forgotten, brave warriors of Grim Batol.', 0),
(50881, 'A dark tide will rise. And with it, this world will return to its rightful owner. All will succumb to His will; all will drown, just as He did.$BThough we were asked not to interfere, we have ensured that the stench of the Stormreaver does not leave this island without first breaking the seal. Enthralled by a former ally—one who seeps deep within the Twilight''s Hammer—they will see it through.$BQueen Azshara and the Sea Witch have yet to make the necessary preparations. Alas, I am told He does not care how long it takes.$BA dark tide will rise, and with it, all of this world will return to the Drowned God.', 0),
(50882, 'I was born under a bad moon, orphaned, exiled, no horns, no place to call my own. Still, the Earthmother whispered to me, "go to the mountain." I didn''t understand, but when I was old enough to work, I began my life as a fisher. 

There was no greater joy I found than fishing for eels. They sold well at market, were good sport to catch, and attracted turtles who had a preference for them as well. Many hours I spent on the beaches of Tanaris and Hinterlands, sitting among the turtles and getting the daily catch of eels.', 0),
(50883, 'On late evenings I believe I could hear the eels speak to me. They too whispered, "go to the mountain." I still did not understand, but I knew eels. They would breed in the ocean, and live their life in fresh water creeks and placid ponds.

So one day I went into the mountains, knowing that there would be no schools of eels, but perhaps I would learn something about myself. Into the reaches of the Hyjalian mountains I went, I heard tale of a lake beneath Nordrasil, the old world tree. Surely the eels would be there.', 0),
(50884, 'I found upon the shores of that lake, other fishers like me, called to the mountain. They hauled great nets teeming with eels, and welcomed me. The Earthmother, the eels, they were right. I found my place with other fishers, my home, my tribe at long last. 

- Rodfather', 0),
(50885, '<Several entries of this logbook date back to a successful streak of plundering and raiding in the past. The crew of this ship, the Bilgerats, seem to be living lavishly in high abundance of their loot on the prolific Plunder Isle, led by their competent captain - whom you haven''t come across yet.>', 0),
(50886, 'We''ve weathered the ruthless storms of this accursed island. If it weren''t for the age-old secrets I had stolen from the old coot''s vaults, my darling''s hull would''ve been cracked open like a crab picked clean by a seagull. Falrevere used to be more cautious, what''s gotten into him?$B$BWe anchored on a small isle north of the mainland. A tiny thing, but it has fresh water and enough wood to build a small compound. For now, however, we will rest. The voyage was long and treacherous, my crew deserves some respite.', 0),
(50887, 'Goro is overseeing the construction; that walking mountain of meat can haul twenty logs at once. I really hit a jackpot with him, how often do you come across a lonely ogre on an atoll deep in the South Seas? The goblin - or ‘green meanie'', how Goro likes to call him - left gold on that island the moment he sailed off without him.', 0),
(50888, 'Crocolisks and murlocs live on this small isle. Meddling creatures, but a good source for food. Snickerfang has been drooling ever since we landed, looking at the wildlife stranded here with us. If you''re unfamiliar with him, he''d scare you straight with his maddening stare and maniacal cackling, but it''s exactly that craziness that makes him so invaluable to me. None of my former cooks - may the depths give them rest - had that much ingenuity. You got a dead rat lying on deck? That gnoll will whip you a feast worthy for kings with it. I am proud to have this crazed hound in my ranks.', 0),
(50889, 'We''ll soon depart our isle and venture onto the mainland. O''Donovan, Moralis, Framwin and Jade will follow me. Framwin already scouted for us before, so we''re prepared for what''s ahead of us. The prospect of gigantic spiders isn''t that exciting, but they''ll be the least of our worries. I got this hunch: this island is unnatural. The storm never ends, the wind is ice-cold and at night, hushed whispers sing mad words into my ears. The sooner we unearth the treasure, the earlier we can depart from his hellish place.', 0),
(50890, '<The handwriting is different from before. More delicate, but written hastily. Inkblots are scattered throughout the page.>$B$BThey took him, they took everyone! Jade and I could escape, but the captain, Moralis and Framwin were captured by those beasts. Their strength was not from this world, and their demon slaves… we were simply overwhelmed. Captain Barbaros fought like an animal, striking down one orc after another, but it was simply not enough. These monsters dragged them off to the castle on the other side of the island. We have to get them back and leave this cursed island immediately!', 0),
(50891, '<The diary is incomplete, but mostly intact. Strange, given how long it must''ve been laying in the fireplace.>', 0),
(50892, 'Second Week of Spring$B$BMother and I went to the market today, as usual. The merchants returned from Kul Tiras again, two whole weeks they were gone. It''s always exciting to see what exotic oddities and produce they bring with them from that place. I''ve never been there, and I probably never will, but just thinking about it excites me. Sometimes the sailors share their stories at the Sorrowmore Inn; grand adventures and narrations of their perilous journeys decorated by obviously fabricated exaggerations. I love listening to them, even if only half of it is true. One time they told the old sailor''s mare of a giant lobster monster, snipping a whole ship in half!', 0),
(50893, 'Third Week of Spring$B$BMatthew helped father on the orchard today, so I had time for myself. Knowing him, he''ll expect me to do something for him in turn, the little snake. I guess it''s only fair, since I was able to spend the day in Breezehaven again because of him. I helped Miss Simmons on the market, as I often do. She''s a kind old lady, and since her husband passed away, she''s got no one but herself. She talks about him so tenderly and softly, the memories of their life are a comforting tale to me. It makes me wish for my own love to bloom one day. Matthew is already engaged to a young lady from Stormwrought, and mother pushes me to do the same. I loathe her when she does it.', 0),
(50894, 'Fifth Week of Spring$B$BThat swine, I swear! If there is one thing Matthew is good at, it''s pushing the worst jobs onto me. He finally collected his favor and had me carry crates around the harbor all day long. Apparently he lost a bet with Ol'' Grizzly at the wharf and was to help him for a few weeks with his work. Typical for him. I''m used to hard labor from helping father at the orchard or carrying things for mother, but this was genuinely grueling. I guess I can''t complain too much, a favor is a favor after all. In the end, this just leaves me with more room to get back at Matthew! Just you wait, you blockhead!', 0),
(50895, 'Sixth Week of Spring$B$BToday was such a wonderful day! There wasn''t much to be done at home, so I had so much time watching the sailors heave up their cargo onto their ships. Their impressive physique and endurance fascinate me greatly, coupled with their enthralling journeys to the most distant corners of the world; simply captivating! What intrigued me the most, however, was this black-haired woman, almost an entire head taller than me! I''ve never seen such a tall woman in my life. I must''ve been so obviously captivated by her, since she actually approached me. Still, she wasn''t actually mad at me staring. Even told me her name: Erika from Stormwind.', 0),
(50896, 'Eight Week of Spring$B$BErika returned to Balor yesterday! We''ve been talking a lot whenever we get the chance to, I''ll probably never tire of listening to her enthralling narrations. It''s as if I''m right there, on deck of the ship with her, braving the raging tides. Sometimes I wish I could just follow her, out to the open sea, out to see what lies beyond the shores of Balor. But mother and father would never allow it. I know it. And I feel this heaviness growing inside my stomach whenever I think about it.$B$BI hate that I do this. Having these thoughts tears at me, it is ugly and destructive. Still, I don''t want to stop spending time with Erika. All I want right now is to be close to her.', 0),
(50897, 'Eleventh Week of Spring$B$BA lot has happened in the last few weeks. Mother gave birth to our beautiful sister, Petra. You could see that Matthew and father really wanted her to be born a boy, but I know they love her dearly. Petra''s chubby little cheeks are just too hard to resist!$B$BAstred, Matthew''s future wife, and her father visited us, too. Discussing wedding preparations. I could see father''s hair turning grey just thinking about how much it''ll cost him! Seeing Astred and Matthew together after such a long time reminded me of how vulnerable my brother can be. The way he gently touches Astred''s pale skin and amber hair, the longing gazes they share when holding hands.', 0),
(50898, 'Usually he is quite the troublemaker for our parents, causing ruckus with the townsfolk or starting yet another tavern brawl. Ever since he met Astred, however, I think he mellowed out a lot. Not that he was not dependable before, but the prospect of him having a wife and a family on his own one day made him realize all this tomfoolery should probably stop sooner than later. He still teases me quite often, but I wouldn''t want it any other way. He''ll always be my brother after all. I do wonder, however. Did I change the same way? When I met Erika?', 0),
(50899, 'First Week of Summer$B$BThe warm sea breeze returns to Balor. Summer is my most cherished time of the year. Feeling the sun on my skin, the smell of flowers in full bloom. I can never get enough of it. I''ve been out for a lot of my free time, using the beautiful gift Erika brought with her from a place called Crestfall. A painter''s kit, colours and brushes. She said the island is famous for its artists and handymen. Personally, I''ve only used charred wood from the fireplace up till now, but so far I''m enjoying it very much. The toads in the pond of the plateau above Breezehaven were great practice. Once I''m getting better, I''ll try painting my family, they''ll love it. I''m sure of it.', 0),
(50900, 'Second Week of Summer$B$BThe sailor''s market opened again a few days ago and I was lucky enough to grab some new paint with the little money I had left. The last week I had spent swinging the brush like my life depended on it, I just can''t help myself. Showing my family the painting I made for them invigorated me so much, even if Father wasn''t all that keen on spending my free time on it. Luckily the others weren''t as grumpy as him. Matthew even asked me to paint Astred and him during their wedding! Never in my life would I have guessed him asking me such a thing. I guess that''s how life goes, you go from one thing to another, not even realising how you got there in the first place.', 0),
(50901, 'Third Week of Summer$B$BThere has been a growing resentment among the sailors coming from Stormwind. They share hushed whispers of wild beasts with green skin and sharp tusks. But they''re not trolls, they say - something unseen and completely new. These savages have been catching caravans offguard and raiding farms. Eating the people they catch, even. Trusting a sailor''s words blindly is a surefire way to lose your money, as we like to say. Usually I love listening to the sailor''s stories, but this is just drunken wish-wash, trying to intimidate the local barmaid.', 0),
(50902, 'Fifth Week of Summer$B$BPreparations for the wedding have been in full force for the last week. As such I''ve been helping a lot on the orchard, taking care of the trees and helping Mother with the household and little Petra. She''s become a lot more active lately and it''s just adorable watching her learn all the wonders Balor has to offer. I can''t wait for our annual Stormwind trip, I''ll show her all of my favourite spots! If all goes well, then the wedding will happen as planned next weekend at the Sorrowmore Inn; Father paid Horace a big sum of gold for food and drink. Weddings on Balor are always a big event, I am so excited!', 0),
(50903, 'Sixth Week of Summer$B$BAstred is downstairs and putting on her dress. It is incredibly beautiful, I''ve never seen such an intricate design before. Mother is helping her, and will join a bit later with Petra. Matthew was pale as chalk when I saw him this morning! I can see he is nervous beyond measure, but evenso: it all comes from a place of great love. Father was grinning from ear to ear at seeing his brave and rowdy son shaking in his boots, it was a sight to behold. I for one will grab my paint and brushes and join the others at the inn. This will be a wonderful day, I can feel it!', 0),
(50904, '<The rest of the book is blank. Whoever wrote this diary met their end that day.>', 0),
(50905, 'Most reverent Lady Prestor,$BOur military efforts are entirely focused on the jousting tournament, just like you ordered. While it still leaves me at unease to not have my best soldiers nearby, I understand the sacrifices I need to make for great change to happen. My brother acts like a hapless child grasping at any straw he can get to bring the situation under control again. The other foolish nobles support him, but they will soon see the truth behind his incompetence. Soon we will remedy my father’s mistake so many years ago, all thanks to your glorious assistance. Please give me more time to strike at the perfect moment, you will not be disappointed, milady.$B$B- Sir Nathaniel Amberwood', 0),
(50906, 'In Loving Memory of Nat$B$BYou were an amazing leader and friend who always put others first.$B$BFrom the players from guilds <Spicy Dwarfburgers> and <Ultima Ratio>', 0),
(50907, 'Draenei divinations are sacred rituals used to scry into the far plains of Draenor. This world does not offer the same quality ingredients found on our homeworld, yet there are suitable substitutes which can work as well, albeit producing a more than dissatisfactory result.', 0),
(50908, 'Arcane Bark$B$BThe wandering trees of this coast tend to the flora, absorbing the innate arcane energy flowing beneath the earth. Their bark is filled with the potent arcane residue, giving them their distinct blue saturation. Most of them traverse the southern woods.', 0),
(50909, 'Ghosts of the past haunt the many ruins of Moonwhisper. Their essences are those of powerful magi, tethering them to this world filled with regret over their past lives. I wonder, how did these ghosts perish and how powerful must their adversary have been for them to have been overpowered?', 0),
(50910, 'The herb that is known as Purple Lotus in this world is enriched with magical properties. Usually we would use the fruits of the Tahn''marani tree, but as we do not have access to them, a clump of Purple Lotus should be enough.', 0),
(50911, 'Lastly, the divine power of Draenethyst is needed to perform the divination. As our own supply is dwindling, finding them scattered across the coast or on the various creatures living here would be your most likely way to acquire one formation.', 0),
(50912, 'Eka''ghar, we have made tremendous strides in establishing our new order. With each day, we convert more lost sheep into our flock, away from the empty lies told for ages by our hollow traditions. The words of our new god have reached the hearts of many plagued by the spiritual fatigue propagated by Moro''gai K''la. Unable to harness the full potential of Draenethyst, they will crumble before our savior''s godly might; and then they will see. They will finally comprehend that their pride in the pitiful and obsolete scriptures of old is misguided. Those with clear hearts will see that our path is the only true way, and they will finally believe and ascend as one of his chosen.', 0),
(50913, 'Once you have completed the delivery, return to the sanctum. It is time we expand our reach even further, to remind this world that it is not beyond salvation.', 0),
(50914, 'Hetaera$B$BA fierce, green-scaled beast roaming the Bay of Storms in the auburn land of Azshara to the south. I have heard its heads are capable of crushing the thickest turtle shell with one bite.', 0),
(50915, 'Typharion$B$BScales red like the burning embers of our ritual fires. It lives in a far away land, far off to the east. Cragged cliffs and a rough ocean beckon this powerful hydra and its servants in the Grim Reaches. The elders say it prefers the waters to the north of its dry fields.', 0),
(50916, 'Scarphanon$B$BBlack as the depths of the Twisting Nether, this hydra commands its kin along the mysterious island of Alcaz, far to the south in the bog named Dustwallow Marsh. Its scales have interested me for quite a while and I am eager to add them to my collection.', 0),
(50917, 'Dear Brave Wildheart, I write this letter with urgency and tragedy. The recent caravan was suspected to be missing over the last few days. I have entrusted the bearer of this note with its inspection, and have concluded that it was ambushed by an unknown attacker. I do know that the Fallen One Draenei were scavenging over the wreckage, but I cannot be certain if they are the true culprit.$B$BThe road between the Moonhoof Village and Retreat is now more dangerous than ever. If another caravan wishes to attend the ceremonies, be sure they are well defended from any would-be attackers.$B$BTorgan of Moonwhisper Retreat.', 0),
(50918, 'Gordnak, how you been? Must be good with all those muscles, huh? It''s Zalwan. We met in Booty Bay before I shipped off to this forsaken rock called Tel''Abim. It''s all monkeys and no fun, let me tell you!$B$BI sent the person carrying this letter to offer assistance to you... Let''s just say things aren''t going well, and I want out. We made some agreements on Booty Bay, and you said you would be willing to take on a job if you were still in Moonwhisper Coast. Same agreement as before, split the profits, and cut this person into it from my end. I need the coin, bad.', 0),
(50919, 'Rahauro, faithful adjutant to Magatha.$B$BI write to request information about the Deathtotem, a secretive group of Grimtotem that seem to be operating within Thousand Needles. This information is paramount to maintaining peace between the tribes, and your cooperation is expected. Do not fail me, I will find out the truth in time.$B$BHigh Chieftain Cairne Bloodhoof', 0),
(50920, 'Lo’sho, Tear of Mu’sha$B$BBlessed are you, Child of Hope, for you were born of pain and yet still embrace us warmly. It is by your presence that hope yet remains, for without it we would not be.$B$BBlessed are you, Curious Child, for giving us the gift of question. It is by your gift that we may have minds of our own, so that we may judge beyond the eyes of the Earthmother with our very own.$B$BBlessed are you, Child of Sorrow, for you allow us to weep and to remember. Better days are coming, yet those that came before must not be forgotten. And so, in you, we find freedom.', 0),
(50921, 'Blessed are you, Matron of Night, for you shine over our heads each cycle. Your warmth and kindness have allowed us, the children of the earth, to survive each turmoil that was sent upon us.$B$BBlessed are you, Matron of Night, for it was your tear that was wept at the cruelty of the world, and from it you gave birth to Lo’sho, our hope. Benevolent Matron, to you we bring praise.$B$BBlessed are you, Matron of Night, for it was you who blessed our tribe. Whether it be grass, mud, or snow, we of the Moonhoof Tribe walk with you still, our hooves leaving trails of crescent moons wherever we step, the symbol of our bond.', 0),
(50922, 'Blessed are you, Patron of Day, for your light keeps Mu’sha shining in the night sky, showing us the blessed bond of siblings and teaching us selfless love.$B$BBlessed are you, Patron of Day, for it is your radiant warmth that blesses the earth, our fur, and our crops. As blinding as your light may be, it still guides us onward.$B$BBlessed are you, Patron of Day, for it was your duty to accept the Tear of Mu’sha as your younger sibling, and it was you who guided Lo’sho toward hope eternal.', 0),
(50923, 'Congratulations, my beloved adventurer! It has been long since last we heard of eachother, or is this the first time? Excuse me, I sometimes lose track of all my little culvers. Nevertheless, what you have accomplished today has been a marvelous display of your skills and abilities. You and your friends were a sight to behold racking your pretty little heads over the mystery of this chest I had borrowed from that dastardly Peroth’arn. It must’ve been very dear to him that he’d safeguard it in such an ominous place.$B$BOh, well. That’s how things go sometimes. I wish you the best of fun with your new toys. Till next we meet again.$B$B~ Phantom Thief C', 0),
(50924, '<The book documents the Fallen One’s journey from them splitting off the Moro’gai up to the present. Some pages offer interesting insights on incidents throughout that time.>', 0),
(50925, 'We have left the others behind at Shimmerstar Lake. So far they have not tried to get in contact with us again, a circumstance I very much welcome. My followers are hard at work establishing new huts and traps for the fish at the pond we have settled. It does not compare to Shimmerstar Lake, but it should provide us with plenty of food, coupled with the wild horned beasts nearby we can hunt. We need to return to normalcy quickly, or else they will lose faith in me.', 0),
(50926, 'Last night, a glistening star illuminated the sky. Shortly after, the star fell onto the coast, much like they did back on Draenor. The impact was right next to our settlement, and while I was able to save most of my followers from the impact, many of our huts and a few unfortunate ones were caught in the blast. A heavy setback, but we will recover. We must.', 0),
(50927, 'Time has passed since the star crashed down to the earth. From the crater, a gigantic crystal emerged. It is not draenethyst, but a rare gift from the Twisting Nether. My followers have recovered from the impact, somewhat atleast. But now new hurdles are laid before our path. Energy from the crystal attracted scaled fiends of azure color. From the way they act, I can feel that they knew about it beforehand. Could they have had a hand in calling it toward this world?', 0),
(50928, 'The situation has become dire. Residue from the crystal seeped into our pond and fouled the fish inside. While my tribesmen still live, eating the fish caused them to convulse in great pain or even fall into a coma. The great horned beasts also migrated mostly to the west, making survival more difficult by the day. Skirmishes with the scaled fiends happen more and more with each passing day and we don''t have the power to fend them off forever.$B$BWe are surrounded by enemies and our food supplies begin to run out. Was this path I’ve chosen for my kin truly the right one? Shall I falter already?', 0),
(50929, 'In my dreams, I experienced a vision. In my inner turmoil, doubts and regrets plagued my mind. Should I accept my misjudgment and return to the Moro’gai? My conviction wavered. It was then that a voice called out to me. A deep and raspy voice, one to know many eons. They spoke of my ambitions, dreams and the loss of trust in my own abilities. And that I could reclaim my lost zeal by seeking allies in the mountains to the south. I was hesitant, but what options had I been left with? My intuition tells me to put my trust in that voice, as desperate as it may be.', 0),
(50930, 'I have sought those mysterious allies; Satyrs, as they call themselves. They are horned and tall creatures, with broad hooves. Their long claws and anguished grimace caused distrust at first, but after speaking with one of their leaders, my doubts were diminished. He called himself Selenaxx, and his people were cast into the darkness as outcasts. They worship a god of the name of Xavius, whose voice I apparently heard in my dream vision. According to Selenaxx, their god is a benevolent one that seeks out those in need and shunned by the world.', 0),
(50931, 'The Satyr offered their help against our adversaries. The magic that they wield is potent and would be a great asset to assure our survival. Perhaps they could even be the key to unlock the Draenethyst''s true potential…  Yet still, hesitation still remains. I shall contemplate on what decision to make. For now, I am relieved to see other kindred spirits in this forsaken world.', 0),
(50932, 'ATTENTION:$B$BRemain silent! Don''t look around at anyone! Someone could be watching you this very moment.$B$BMy name is Thorinn Darkgrovel, $N. I train those willing to seek knowledge and greater power from... worlds beyond. I see you have shown interest in magic that surpasses that of the infantile Azurestone Order. Fret not, I''ve been asked to get in touch with you discretely and inform you that I can train you further in a real form of magic.$B$BWhen you can, come find me in the back of Anvilmar.$B$B-Thorinn Darkgrovel, Warlock Trainer', 0),
(50933, 'Blessed are you, $N, child of the Earth. The ancestors whisper your name in my ears with a joy that cannot easily be expressed. As such, I have sent word for you to meet me as soon as possible. We have much to discuss, for I am told you have made it your goal to worship the Three Celestial Siblings.$B$BAs you gather wit and wisdom here in the Red Cloud Mesa, your potential will surely reveal itself. Curiosity stirs in my mind. I wonder whether you will remain a disciplined devotee of all three, or find either An’she, Mu’sha, or Lo’sho closer to your heart and dedicate yourself to one above the others.', 0),
(50934, 'Moondancer.$B$BWere you always this much of an imbecile? I have waited for hours. Last we spoke I told you how important our time is and yet you fail me in my hours of most need. You used to be such a dependable apprentice. No matter. I trust you have not somehow managed to get yourself killed by the naga of Nendis and will find this letter once you arrive.$B$BI have the artifact, I leave its coffer behind for you to find. After all, I need you to come find me. Zandaxxius was right, this artefact holds a great power. I am heading towards the Temple of Elunaris, I am certain Lo’sho will answer my prayers and fuel me with the required strength to wield this power. I can finally have my vengeance on Moonhoof and his righteous patron. I wonder how we will react when he witnesses it all. Join me swiftly, Moondancer. We have work to do.', 0),
(50935, 'The Sun had finally set on the blue lands of Moonwhisper Coast. With nightfall, its usual shepherd did not gaze upon the land. The Moon was nowhere to be seen. And yet, that was not the sole surprise, for even the youngest of the siblings, the Blue Child, was also missing. An ill sign for the children of the Earth. A superstitious folk, the Tauren believed this to be an omen of immediate chaos. Ruckus could be heard from Moonhoof Village. The celestials were missing, and so was the Elder Chieftain. Beyond their desperation, the old chieftain slowly tapped his mighty hooves on the blue grass, leaving crescent moons in the mud with each step. He approached the dreaded Grove in solemn silence.', 0),
(50936, 'He carried no torch, no weapon. His white fur, pale as freshly fallen snow, glimmered faintly beneath the stars. The only garment upon him was a simple kilt. His brown mane shimmered gold beneath the night as orbs of light encircled his rugged frame. Fireflies eagerly danced about him, guiding his movements through the darkness. As he pressed deeper into the Grove, he felt the gaze of the trees heavy upon the back of his neck. He was being watched. The branches stretched toward him with disdain, with unease even, yet they shrank back at once when they felt the heat of the living flame within him.', 0),
(50937, 'With a huff and a puff, the old Tauren finally halted. “You drink alone tonight,” he muttered, his gaze fixed upon the figure seated at a rough-hewn wooden table, sipping from a cup. Moths drifted toward him, abandoning the other Tauren’s shadow to seek the light of his fireflies. He smiled faintly, exhaling through his nose with a sound like a scoff. “You walk my Grove as though you own it, elder brother,” came a voice from behind the empty cup. A pale hand reached for the pitcher, seeking a refill.', 0),
(50938, '“You still call me brother. Odd,” the old chieftain said. “Yet here you are, far from your duties, forsaking that which gave you life. You parade yourself amidst the children of chaos and bend the children of the Earth to that chaos as well.” His frown deepened, arms folding across his chest. He looked every bit the elder sibling there to discipline the younger. “Is it so strange? You came here to scold me, playing the role of my elder brother. I may as well grant you the satisfaction. You know well how I love theatrics.”', 0),
(50939, 'This Tauren’s fur was pale as well, but it bore the pallor of death rather than the pallor of snow. His eyes glimmered the same blue as the younger Moon. Despite his mockery, there was amusement in his gaze. “Enough quarreling, elder. Join me for a glass.” He raised his cup. “Mm. Have your servants abandoned you to your own drunken ruin?” Moonhoof asked as he approached. “I dismissed them. They could not bear the sight of your holiness.” “Enough games, brother. You know why I am here.” The elder sat beside him.', 0),
(50940, 'Mothshroud sighed heavily. “And what, pray tell, would that be?” Moonhoof’s jaw tightened. “Let us begin with the fact that you are possessing that poor soul’s body.” “As if you are any better. What should your actions be named, then? A blessing? A gift bestowed by the mighty, the shining…” “Enough. This one prayed for it.” Moonhoof’s brow furrowed. “So did this one,” Mothshroud said, arching a brow. “Which is precisely the problem, sibling. Why give solace to these chaotic souls? You walk among them as though they were your own. They wish for nothing but ruin. You even took in the wretched satyr. They… they are part of the reason she—” He faltered, his voice breaking.', 0),
(50941, '“You cannot lay that blame at my feet. Her actions were hers alone.” “But you were meant to bring hope!” Moonhoof rose sharply, his hands clasping the back of his head in anguish. “And I still do, even among your chosen,” Mothshroud said, sipping his cup. “But I was born of pain. You know that whatever you both tried to weave could not last. I do not command them. They will follow their own will. Unlike our sibling, who basks in the adoration of the Night’s children, I walk openly among mine. We are all seen here.” “You fool. Is it jealousy that drives you?”', 0),
(50942, '“Must you think so little of me, elder brother? No, I am not jealous. She may keep her pets. I have my own followers, and I will grant them precisely what they desire: hope or despair, order or chaos. And if you have come to stop me, may the stronger will prevail.” He drained his glass. “Now leave my Grove and never return. We were never meant to meet upon these lands.” “You are making a grave mistake, sibling. The Earth will mourn your choice, and I will not stand idle. My followers will have my blessings, and when they rise to trample yours, remember: this was your doing.” Moonhoof began to stamp the earth once more, leaving a crescent moon mark with each step.', 0),
(50943, '“Always the self-appointed justiciar,” Mothshroud hissed, shattering the cup in his hand. “So be it. War it is.” As Mothshroud turned away, he stalked the Grove, leaving strange marks behind him. Before vanishing into the dark, he cast his gaze skyward and saw that the Moon had returned. Yet as its light bathed the land, another presence emerged beside it: the Blue Child, restored, but changed. Cold and distant, he drifted away from his elder, as though seeking to escape.', 0),
(50944, 'What this foretold for the children of the Earth, for Moonwhisper Coast, none could say. But the omens were dire, for kin now stood upon paths that would cross beneath the silent gaze of the Earthmother, and the blue grass would soon drink the blood of those they once held dear.', '');

